    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-02-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-02-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="366"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Porter</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-02-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 20, 1902</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 969.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I duly received your dispatch<note n="c"
                        xml:id="d366fnc">Printed <ref target="#pg_275">page 275</ref>.</note> of
                    February 3, inclosing a copy of a memorandum which had been telegraphed to our
                    representatives at Pekin and St. Petersburg, regarding Russian negotiations with
                    China to secure extensive concessions in Manchuria.</p>
                <p>I gave a copy, as directed, to Mr. Delcassé, who appeared not to have received
                    information of any steps on the part of Russia looking to a departure from the
                    principle of the open door and equal treatment in China to all commercial
                    nations. He said in all his talks and communications with officials of the
                    Russian Government there had been repeated declarations made regarding that
                    country’s determination to maintain the policy of the open door and to adhere to
                    the previously expressed intention to withdraw from Manchuria as soon as it
                    could safely be done. I do not give his exact words, but it is evident that he
                    believes in the good faith of Russia regarding these matters. He did not say
                    whether he knew any of the details regarding negotiations looking to exclusive
                    concessions.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Horace Porter.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
